        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1971-11-17T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1971-11-17T00:00:00-05:00" n="305"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d305">
                <head>305. Memorandum From the President’s Assistant for National Security Affairs
                        (<persName corresp="#p_KHA1" type="from">Kissinger</persName>) to Secretary
                    of State <persName corresp="#p_RWP1" type="to">Rogers</persName> and the
                    Director of the Arms Control and Disarmament Agency
                        (<persName>Smith</persName>)<note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d305fn1"
                        >Source: National Archives, Nixon Presidential Materials, <gloss
                            target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Box 229, Agency Files, Department of
                        Defense, volume 14, Nov–Dec 1971. Confidential. A copy was sent to <persName
                            corresp="#p_LMR2">Laird</persName>, <persName corresp="#p_SJR1"
                            >Schlesinger</persName>, and <persName corresp="#p_MTH1"
                            >Moorer</persName>.</note>
                    <note n="2" type="summary" xml:id="d305fn2">The President issued directions for
                        clearance of statements and instructions concerning nuclear test ban
                        policy.</note>
                </head>
                <dateline>
                    <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1971-11-17"
                        >November 17, 1971</date>
                </dateline>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT:</head>
                    <item>Clearance of Statements and Instructions Concerning Nuclear Test Ban
                        Policy</item>
                </list>
                <p>The President has directed that official statements and instructions to
                    delegations at the United Nations and the Conference of the Committee on
                    Disarmament concerning U.S. nuclear test ban policy will be cleared at the White
                    House.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Henry A. Kissinger</persName>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
